        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: We expect a single dish flux density of 3.8 mJy in Band 6. (for details see the scientific justification, Sect. 2.2) Using our model image scaled to this flux density, the web-based the ALMA simulator gave a peak flux density of 0.23 mJy/beam (see Fig 1 in the scientific justification). With on-source integration time of 2 hours and aggregate bandwidth of 7.495 GHz, we will reach a continuum sensitivity of 0.014 mJy, thus an SNR of almost 17. For the line peak flux density, the expected value (from our model) is 60 mJy, thus the line can be detected during the continuum observation with high SNR. 
Imaging: The source has no extended component (compared to the maximum recoverable scale). The project depends on the high angular resolution of the array, the needed resolution, 0.18 as is essential.
Correlator setup: We intend to map the (relatively weak) dust distribution in Band 6, therefore we need as large bandwidth as can obtained. We want to include one CO line observation in the lowest subband as well. With the proposed setup, we do not lose significant amount of bandwidth (thus sensitivity) from the continuum part of the project, but the line can be still adequately resolved in frequency space. (To increase the spatial resolution the subbands are moved to the higher part of the band.)
Calibration: No special calibration strategy needed.
Bandpass accuracy: NA
Scheduling/time constraints: NA
Data rate: NA
Special constraints on standard observing modes: NA</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
